16:10.37brlcadStragus: a bit more complicated. this isn't allocation-related, it's a handle to reference counted memory mapped files that are stored in a hash -- code pulled the handle from the hash to see if it was there... closed it (mind you it's still in the hash), then went to use it again.  that was all good and fine until it came time to clean up and shut down, and a bit of naive code simply iterated over the
16:10.42brlcadhash and closed everything (because it should only be there if it's open)
16:11.14brlcadcould've caught that it was already closed, but that would have just masked the mistake.  just took a bit to find where it was getting closd prematurely

15:22.33brlcadStragus: that's a huge it-depends, particularly with respect to whatever agreement you have with SURVICE.  if you don't have something saying otherwise, using personal code for work can result in a transfer of ownership to an employer.  if that has occurred, as opposed to some irrevocable worldwide unlimited license use, then you would not be able to sell it to this new 3rd party.  I would recommend
15:22.40brlcadagainst that anyways as people with that mindset are likely to want to exercise their ownership, otherwise they wouldn't ask for that.
15:23.54brlcadIf you want to sell and think you still have rights to do so, you could offer them a non-exclusive license (not copyright transfer)
15:25.43brlcadStragus: if you can't put a standard flexible license on it (like apache2 or mit etc) and be done with it, that would be highly suspicious..
15:31.29Stragusbrlcad: I have an agreement with SURVICE, I often bring in personal code, I keep the copyright and both SURVICE and U.S. government gets unlimited/unrestricted/perpetual/transcendental rights
15:32.34StragusI don't really want to sell anything, the guy just wants to bring the code in his project, and he wants uniform copyright over all the code for reasons
15:35.09StragusAnd he says I would still get unlimited/unrestricted rights to the code, so I could keep using it anywhere (even in SURVICE and elsewhere?...)
15:35.17StragusAlso, argh, what a mess
15:41.09*** join/#brlcad kintel (~textual@unaffiliated/kintel)
16:21.24brlcadStragus: I wouldn't without consulting a lawyer for those reasons.  smells fishy under guise of "he just wants ... for reasons".  well you just want to keep copyright for ... reasons too.  let him have unlimited unrestricted rights.  unless he's offering you a very large pile of cash and you're okay with the worst case happening (e.g., he sues you for using his code)
16:23.32brlcadyou could very easily accidentally agree to revocable rights, so you can keep using it today anywhere, but maybe not tomorrow
16:25.25brlcadhe could even in good faith give you proper unlimited rights and then deliver/sell the code to some other company who might then sue you for infringement.  You'd win the lawsuit, of course, just after going bankrupt defending yourself.

18:42.28cad_zulip@**Himanshu Sekhar Nayak**: btw what's the difference between default build and release build mentioned in http://brlcad.org/wiki/Building_from_SVN#Configure_the_build_system_with_CMake ?
18:44.04*** join/#brlcad Stragus (~alexis@191.109.76.1)
18:50.48cad_zulip@**Erik**: ```quote
18:50.48cad_zuliphey @**Erik** :)
18:50.48cad_zulip```
18:50.48cad_zulipHi, is there something I can help with?
18:51.59cad_zulip@**Erik**: default build has some optimizations turned off and some debugging turned on, release is "for performance", do a default build
18:52.25cad_zulip@**Daniel Rossberg**: CMake usually detects already existing libraries on you system and uses them instead of their versions provided with the BRL-CAD source code (usually in the src/other directory). DBRLCAD_BUNDLED_LIBS=ON demands to use always the version which comes with the BRL-CAD source code.
18:52.25cad_zulipThere are usually two main build types: Debug and Release. Debug contains additional code/data to match it with the source code. I.e., it can be said which code part belongs to which source code line and what the variables' values are.
18:52.25cad_zulipThe release build is a usually speed optimized build with no debug information and variables often often don't have a memory address, because they live in processor registers only (if possible).
18:53.30cad_zulip@**Erik**: (Easy bugs in debug builds can very easily become difficult bugs in release mode due to compiler optimization methods, all  ya'll should be avoiding release unless you know what you're doing)
19:07.42cad_zulip@**Himanshu Sekhar Nayak**: thanks for info @**Erik** @**Daniel Rossberg**
